# **ASSAULT PHASE**

![][image13]

During the assault phase, the active player follows the sequence below to charge eligible units into close combat and resolve melee engagements.  

#### **STEP 1: DECLARE CHARGES**

#### **STEP 2: ASSAULT MOVES & REACTIONS**

#### **STEP 3: RESOLVE MELEE ENGAGEMENTS**

#### **STEP 4: CLOSE COMBAT RESULTS**

## **STEP 1: DECLARE CHARGES**

In STEP 1, the active player selects unengaged units that wish to **CHARGE**, and declares the targets for their charges.  The active player may also select already engaged units and declare they are attempting to **WITHDRAW** from the melee engagement.  After declaring any desired charges or withdrawals, proceed to STEP 2\.

### Declare Charges

The active player selects a unit they wish to charge with and declares which unit they intend to charge.

#### **CHARING ELIGIBILITY**

In order for a unit to be eligible to charge, the following conditions must be met:

* The charging unit must be unengaged.  
* The charging unit may not have made an advance move, unless abilities allow the unit to advance and charge.  
* The charging unit may not have shot this turn, unless all fired weapons allow charging after shooting (e.g. Assault Weapons).  
* The charging unit may not be **pinned** or **broken**.

#### **DECLARE CHARGE TARGET**

A unit that is eligible to charge declares a target to charge, subject to the below conditions:

* **PICKING A TARGET:** Charges may only be declared against an opposing unit that the charging unit shot at in the shooting phase.  If the charging unit did not shoot at all, it may declare a charge against any opposing unit(s).  
  * **CHARGING MULTIPLE UNITS:** Charges may be declared against more than one unit. If the charging unit shot at any opposing unit(s) this turn, at least one of the charge targets must be a unit shot at. If the charging unit had **SPLIT FIRE**, it must declare a charge against at least one of the  target units.    
  * **TRANSPORTS & EMBARKED UNITS**: If a unit shot at a transport and passengers were forced to disembark during the same shooting phase (e.g. the vehicle was destroyed), the shooting unit may declare a change against those disembarked passengers.

### Declare Withdrawals {#declare-withdrawals}

The active player may select a unit that is already in a melee engagement and declare that they wish to voluntarily withdraw the unit from the engagement (see [VOLUNTARY WITHDRAWALS](#voluntary-withdrawals)). The withdrawal move is resolved below in Step 2\.

## **STEP 2: ASSAULT MOVES & REACTIONS**

In STEP 2, the active player selects a unit that declared a charge or withdrawal and resolves that movement action.  Opposing units that are unengaged may choose to **STAND & SHOOT\!** as a reaction to being charged.  Charging and withdrawing units can be resolved in the order of the active player’s choosing. After resolving all declared charge moves, withdrawal moves, and STAND & SHOOT\! reactions, proceed to STEP 3 to resolve each melee engagement.

### Charge Moves

When a unit is select to resolve its charge, the following process is used:

#### **DETERMINE CHARGE SUCCESS:**

* **CHECK CHARGE DISTANCE:** The unit targeted by the charge move must be within the **charge distance of 6”**, unless the unit has a special rule granting it a longer distance charge.   
  * **CHARGE FAILS:** If no charging models are within the charge distance of a model in the declared target, then the charge fails and the unit is not moved.  
  * **CHARGE SUCCESSFUL:** If a charging model IS within the charge distance of at least one model in the declared target, then the charge will be successful.  
* **DIFFICULT TERRAIN:** Charge moves are affected by difficult terrain and a difficult terrain test must be taken AND allow enough movement for at least one charging model to reach a target model in base to base contact for the charge to be successful.  Roll difficult terrain tests at this time to determine charge success.  
* **STAND & SHOOT REACTION:** Once a charge is determined to be successful, the charge target, if unengaged, may choose to perform a **STAND & SHOOT\!** reaction against the unit resolving its charge (see [STAND & SHOOT\!](#stand-&-shoot!))

#### **PERFORM CHARGE MOVE**

The following steps are used to resolve a charge move:

* Starting with the closest model in the charging unit to the charge target, the active player must move that model up to 6” (or more if allowed by a special rule) into base-to-base contact with any model in the charge target.  The charge move does not have to be between the closest two models in the respective units.    
* Once completed, remaining models, in order of nearest to farthest, complete their charges by moving into base-to-base contact with an enemy model OR being moved to within 1” of a friendly model in the same unit that is in base-to-base contact with an enemy if possible.  
* After completing a charge move, the charged target may be eligible to **PILE-IN** (see [PILE-IN MOVES](#pile-in-moves))


#### **ADDITIONAL CHARGING DETAILS**

* **RESOLVING CHARGES AGAINST MULTIPLE UNITS:**  At least one declared charge target unit must be in a successful charge range.   
  * If the charging unit fired at an enemy unit, they must be able to engage that unit.   
  * If the charging unit cannot engage at least one target unit they shot at, the charge fails and no movement occurs.  
* **MOVING NEAR ENEMY MODELS:** Charging units are permitted to move within 1” of enemy units, regardless of whether it is the charge target or not, but may not contact units in base-to-base contact other than declared charge target(s).  
* **COHERENCY & CHARGING MULTIPLE UNITS**: The active player cannot complete a charge move against multiple units if completing all of the charge moves would bring the unit out of coherency.  If necessary, charging models may be positioned to bridge a gap coherency, even if it means that such a model is unengaged when it otherwise might be able to be.

* ##### **CHARGING OVER OBSTACLES:** It may be the case that models charging over obstacles and/or through cover to reach their target have enough movement to reach base-to-base contact but cannot be physically placed in base-to-base contact due to the physical arrangement of the terrain features.  In these cases, charging models may be placed in the closest stable position and still be counted as being in base-to-base contact.

* **STRUCTURES & BUILDING LEVELS:** Models may engage enemy models between building levels even if the models are not on the same level.  Models positioned within 1” horizontally and one level above or below their target are also treated as being engaged.

### Stand & Shoot\! {#stand-&-shoot!}

#### **WHEN CAN A UNIT TAKE STAND & SHOOT\! REACTION?**

* Immediately after a charge is determined to be successful against an unengaged unit, but before making the charge move, the unengaged unit may perform a **STAND & SHOOT\!** reaction against the charging unit .  
* The following additional restrictions apply to when a unit can Stand & Shoot\!:   
  * The unit may not have fired previously this turn (i.e. Overwatch of Return Fire\!).  
  * The unit may not have Gone to Ground (or Jinked) this turn.  
  * The unit may not be Broken or Pinned.  
  * The unit must be unengaged.  
  * The unit may not split fire.  
  * **VEHICLES** may never Stand & Shoot\!


#### **RESOLVING STAND & SHOOT\!**

* The unit resolving Stand & Shoot\! attacks do so using the **LIMITED FIRE** rules (see [LIMITED FIRE](#limited-fire))  
* Return fire inflicts casualties before any of the charging units make their charge moves.  
* If, due to casualty removals, the charging unit can no longer reach one of its charge targets, it is still moved as far as possible towards its declared target. Additionally, the target must make a **Pile-In Move** to engage the charging unit if possible.  
* *IMPORTANT REMINDER:* Units shooting with limited fire as a result of the Return Fire\! Reaction must also shoot with limited fire on their own next turn and also suffer penalties in assaults during the current turn.

### Pile-in Moves {#pile-in-moves}

#### **WHEN TO MAKE PILE-IN MOVES?**

* Immediately after a charging unit completes its moves, un-engaged models in the charged unit(s) must **PILE-IN**.  
* At the end of close combat, models in units that remain locked in close combat (see STEP 4\) must **PILE-IN**.

#### **RESOLVING PILE-IN MOVES**

* Unengaged models in a unit (i.e. those not in base-to-base contact with an opposing unit or within 1” of a friendly model that is) that must make a pile in move do so as follows:  
  * Proceeding sequentially with the closest unengaged model, each model moves **up to 6”** to get into base-to-base contact with a charging model. If that is not possible, the model must be moved as close to an enemy model as possible and be within 1” of a friendly model that is in base-to-base contact.   
  * The overall series of pile-in moves should strive to engage as many models as possible.

### Voluntary Withdrawals {#voluntary-withdrawals}

Units belonging to the active player that are already engaged in close combat at the start of their assault phase may attempt to voluntarily withdraw from close combat during this step in the assault phase.

* Units may attempt to withdraw before, between, or after other charge or withdrawal moves are made.  
* A unit that is withdrawing immediately **BREAKS** and performs a **FALL BACK** move (see [FALLING BACK](#falling-back)).  
* If the opposing unit is no longer engaged with any of the active player’s units, they may choose to **PURSUE** or **CONSOLIDATE** (see [CLOSE COMBAT RESULTS](#step-4:-close-combat-results) below). 

## **STEP 3: RESOLVE MELEE ENGAGEMENTS**

In STEP 3, both players’ units that are engaged in close combat have an opportunity to attack.  First, the active player chooses a **MELEE ENGAGEMENT** to resolve. Within that engagement, **DETERMINE ENGAGED MODELS**. work out the **ATTACK ORDER**, and lastly **RESOLVE ATTACKS**. After all melee attacks are resolved in the engagement, the active player chooses a subsequent melee engagement to resolve and so on.  Once all melee engagements are resolved, proceed to STEP 3\.

### Determine Engaged Models

* **MELEE ENGAGEMENT:** A melee engagement is all of the units and models that are collectively engaged with one another and forming a single group.  When resolving melee attacks, all attacks from both sides of the engagement are resolved completely before moving onto a subsequent engagement.   
* **ENGAGED MODELS:** At the start of a Melee Engagement, every model of both players that are in base-to-base contact with an opposing model or that is within 1” of a friendly model that is in base-to-base contact with an opposing model are ENGAGED.    
  * Engaged Models count as engaged throughout the resolution of melee engagement, regardless of how casualties at different initiative steps may occur.   
  * Models charging over obstacles may be counted as in base-to-base contact even if not physically touching.  Likewise, models one level above or below their target are counted as engaged.  
* **VEHICLES**: Non-Walker Vehicles in base-to-base (or hull-to-hull) contact count as engaged in close combat, but are not locked in close combat (i.e. they are free to move out of close combat in their own movement phase).  
  * **WALKERS** ARE engaged AND locked in close combat (the same as for figurine models).

### Attack Order

* **INITIATIVE ORDER:** The order that models attack within an individual engagement is determined by their respective **INITIATIVE** values.  The model(s) with the highest initiative attack first, working down to the lowest initiative value.  If models on both sides are tied for a given initiative value, those attacks are resolved simultaneously (i.e. wounds and casualties are noted but not applied until after the other model(s) attack).  
* **CHARGING THROUGH COVER**: If a charged unit was unengaged at the start of the current assault phase and any charging models were required to move through cover as part of their charge move, then those charging models are treated as having Initiative 1 in the current turn’s assault phase.   
* **GRENADES:** Grenades are used during assaults to influence the attack order.  
  * **ASSAULT GRENADES:** Any model equipped with a weapon with the **Grenade** Special Rule that charged into melee combat this turn ignores the initiative penalty for charging through cover (the models attack at its normal initiative value).  
  * **DEFENSIVE GRENADES**: If a unit with a weapon with the Defensive Grenade Special Rule was unengaged at the start of the current assault phase and charged this turn, all charging units lose their bonus attack for charging (counts as a **DISORDERED CHARGE**).  
    * If a unit is listed as having Defensive Grenades without a profile, use the following profile:

| Name | S | AP | Special Rules |
| :---- | :---: | :---: | :---- |
| Defensive Grenade | 1 | \- | Assault 1, Defensive Grenade, Blast, Blind |

* *REMINDER FOR REACTING UNITS*: Units which performed **Return Fire\!** or **Stand & Shoot\!** reactions lose all benefits for being in cover, attack at Initiative 1 instead of their normal initiative, and lose any bonus attacks (they only attack with their normal attack characteristic).

### Resolving Melee Attacks {#resolving-melee-attacks}

The following process is used for resolving melee attacks within a specific melee engagement.

#### **1\) DETERMINE NUMBER OF ATTACKS**

* **ATTACK CHARACTERISTIC:** When it is a model’s turn to make its attacks in an engagement, it attacks a number of times equal to its attack characteristic.  
* **TWO CLOSE COMBAT WEAPONS:** Models armed with two or more close combat weapons, which are either melee or pistol weapons, gains \+1 attack. While pistols count towards having a second melee weapon, the pistol itself is not fired in close combat and its weapon profile is not be used for resolving melee attacks.  
* **CHARGING MODELS:** Models that charged gain \+1 attack for the current turn only.  
  * **DISORDERED CHARGE**: Units do not gain their charge bonus when (A) charging out of a non-assault vehicle; (B) charging after deep-striking; and (C) charging enemy units with defensive grenades. Other situations may also cause a disordered charge.  
* **REACTING UNITS:** Units which performed **Return Fire\!** or **Stand & Shoot\!** reactions only make a number of attacks equal to their attack characteristic, and do not gain bonus attacks for having multiple weapons, etc.  
* **DETERMINE WEAPONS:** Models with no melee weapons or with generic close combat weapons attack using the model’s own STRENGTH characteristic.  If a model has different melee weapons, the weapon’s profile may be used for any or all attacks. If a model has multiple melee weapons, the owning player decides how to allocate its attacks between the weapons.


#### **2\) DETERMINE TARGET FOR MELEE ATTACKS**

* A model will allocate all of its attacks against the unit it is engaged with, either by being in base-to-base contact with an enemy or within 1” of a friendly model in base-to-base contact.  
* If a model is in base-to-base contact with models from multiple different opposing units, and/or within 1” of friendly models that are engaged with different units, the attacker must declare which of its attacks are being directed towards which enemy unit.


#### **3\) ROLL TO HIT: MELEE ATTACKS**

* All attacks from one unit against another that occur at the same initiative step are rolled together.  
* **WEAPON SKILL:** Each model rolls to hit using its own weapon skill versus the weapon skill of the unit it is making an attack against (see [ROLL TO HIT: MELEE ATTACKS](#roll-to-hit:-melee-attacks)).  
* **TARGET UNITS WITH MIXED WEAPON SKILLS:** If the target unit contains models with multiple weapon skills, use whichever weapon skill is in the majority.  In the case of a tie for majority, use the higher of the tied values.


#### **4\) ROLL TO WOUND: MELEE ATTACKS**

* Successful hits are then rolled as a group to wound, using the attacking model’s strength value or the strength of the melee weapon making the attack.    
* **MIXED TOUGHNESS IN TARGET UNIT:** If the target unit has models with different toughness values, use the toughness value that is in the majority among models in the target unit to determine the wound roll needed.  If no majority exists, use the highest toughness value from among the tied values.

#### **5\) ALLOCATE WOUNDS**

* After all wounds rolls are made, the target unit’s owner allocates successful wounds to **ENGAGED MODELS** in the target unit.  Each engaged model must be allocated a wound before any other engaged model is allocated a second wound (and so on until all wounds are allocated).  
* Any specific melee hit and resulting wound can be allocated to any engaged model in the unit.


#### **6\) DETERMINE & ROLL SAVINGS THROWS** 

* After wounds are allocated, wounded models must take a saving throw using the armor save or invulnerable save available to them.  
* Models may not take cover saves when in a melee engagement.


#### **7\) APPLY WOUNDS & REMOVE CASUALTIES**

* Each failed saving throw results in an **unsaved wound,** which the defender must apply to their unit.  
* Unsaved wounds may be applied to any **ENGAGED MODEL** in the unit, with the exception that unsaved wounds must be first applied to already wounded models first (see [REMOVING CASUALTIES](#removing-casualties)).  
  * If all engaged models in the target unit are removed, any additional unsaved wounds that remain to be applied are ignored and are not transferred to non-engaged models.

## **STEP 4: CLOSE COMBAT RESULTS** {#step-4:-close-combat-results}

After all attacks in all melee engagements are resolved, the result of each engagement is determined.  The active player selects a melee engagement of their choice, determines the results, and then moves onto resolving a subsequent melee engagement, and so on until all melee engagements are resolved.

### Determine The Winning Side

* Total up the number of **UNSAVED WOUNDS** that each side suffered across all of their units participating in the selected melee engagement. The side that suffered more unsaved wounds is the **LOSING SIDE,** and the opposing player is the **WINNING SIDE**.  
  * Against Walkers, each penetrating or glancing hit counts as a wound (see [VEHICLES IN ASSAULT](#vehicles-in-assault)).  
* If both sides suffered the same number of unsaved wounds, then the melee engagement is a draw and will continue on the next player turn\!  
* If one side destroyed all models on the opposing side, they automatically win the melee engagement, even if they suffered more unsaved wounds.  
* All units in the losing side must take a **BREAK TEST**.

### Break Test

* **BREAK TEST**: Units that lost the engagement must take a break test by performing a leadership test for the unit, using the unit’s highest leadership. Break tests are a morale test subject to the following additional modifiers:  
  * **\-1 for every three total unsaved wounds, or part thereof, the losing side lost *by***   
    *(-1 Ld for losing by 1-3 wounds, \-2 for losing by 4-6 wounds, etc.)*  
  * \-1if the unit is at half-strength or below (i.e. below 50% of its starting strength)  
  * \-1 if the unit is out of coherency  
* **FAILED BREAK TESTS:** Each unit that fails their break test becomes **BROKEN** and immediately **RETREATS.**  
  * **RETREAT**: Retreating units move D6 \+ Initiative (highest value the unit) in inches away from the engagement, as if performing a fall back move (and is not affected by difficult terrain)  
  * Units retreating due to losing an engagement may move directly through enemy figurine models that they were engaged with, but may not stop on top of any enemy models or within 1” of other enemies.  
* **PASSED BREAK TESTS:** Each unit that passes their break test carries on fighting and does not fall back. Each unit that passed its break test and all the units on the winning side remain engaged and locked in the melee engagement \- even if no individual models are still in base-to-base contact.  
* **VOLUNTARILY BREAKING:** Units that are required to make a break test **may** choose to voluntarily break (i.e. chose to fail the break test). Units voluntarily breaking may still be pursued (see PURSUITS & CONSOLIDATIONS).

### Pursuits & Consolidations

* **PILE-IN:** If any units passed their break tests, both sides’ remaining units and models that were part of the engagement must make a **PILE IN MOVE** (see PILE IN), starting with the active player.  Resolve pile in moves AFTER resolving any FALL BACK moves for units that failed their break test. The fight will continue on the next player turn\!  
* **PURSUIT:** Units on the winning side will attempt to pursue falling back units, unless they are still locked in the melee engagement with another opposing unit that did not break.  
  * A unit making a pursuit moves D6 \+ Initiative (highest value unit) inches towards the falling back unit to get into base to base contact.  The pursuing unit may move within 1” of any falling back units, but may not move within 1” of other opposing units.  
  * Pursuit moves are not slowed by difficult terrain.  
  * If no model pursuing model is able to move into base to base contact then the pursuing unit does not conduct any pursuit moves and remains in place where it is.  
  * **PURSUIT ATTACKS:** After making the pursuit move, each pursuing model deals one automatic close combat hit (using any of the model’s equipped weapons) to a single model it is in base-to-base contact with. The pursuing unit’s owner chooses where these wounds are allocated.  
  * After inflicting wounds, if any models are still in base-to-base contact or within 1” of a pursued model, the respective units remain engaged and locked into hand-to-hand combat. If this occurs, the pursued unit(s) are no longer considered broken.  No additional pile in movements occur this turn (but will take place at the start of the next assault phase). If no models are in base-to-base contact or within 1”, then neither unit is engaged any longer.  
* **RESTRAINT** **TEST**: If the winning unit does NOT wish to pursue the falling back unit, they must instead take a restraint test, which is a leadership test.  If the test passes, the unit may **CONSOLIDATE** instead of pursuing the falling back unit.    
  * **WITHDRAWING UNITS:** If a unit chooses to take a restraint test in response to pursuing an opposing unit that voluntarily withdrew, the restraint test automatically passes.  
* **CONSOLIDATION**: Units on the winning side that are no longer engaged with any opposing units, due to all opposing units being destroyed and/or passing a restraint test, may make a consolidation move of up to 3”.    
  * Consolidation moves must be used to move the unit back into coherency.    
  * **RE-ENGAGEMENT:** Consolidation moves may be used to move the consolidating unit into base-to-base contact with enemy units (the same unit they previously fought or a different unit), and immediately locks that unit into a melee engagement. No pile in moves occur at this time and the new melee engagement will be resolved next turn.   
  * **OVERRUN\!:** If a unit is able to make a consolidation move in the same turn that it charges, instead of taking a normal 3” consolidation move, the unit may choose to instead consolidate up to D6”.  The results of the die stand, and the normal 3” consolidation cannot be taken after rolling the dice.  
  * **VEHICLES**: Non-Walker vehicles do not lock units in hand to hand combat. As such, non-walker vehicles and any units attacking such vehicles may not take consolidation moves. The unit may be eligible to consolidate or pursue if engaged and locked in combat with other enemy units as normal.

